{{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = The Hon. | name = Frederick Murray Blois | honorific-suffix = | image = | office = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for Colchester-Hants, Nova Scotia | appointed = [[John Diefenbaker]] | term_start = 1960 | term_end = 1976 | office2 = Member of the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] for Colchester | predecessor2 = | successor2 = | term_start2 = 1937 | term_end2 = 1945 | birth_date = {{birth date|1893|3|30}} | birth_place = Gore District, Nova Scotia | death_date = {{death date and age|1984|8|3|1893|3|30}} | death_place = | nationality = | spouse = | party = [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | occupation = | profession = | religion = }} '''Frederick Murray Blois''' (March 30, 1893 &ndash; August 3, 1984) was a [[Canadian]] politician.
Born in [[Gore District, Nova Scotia|Gore District]], [[Nova Scotia]], he was a member of the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] for eight years starting in 1937 and was [[Conservative Party of Nova Scotia|Conservative Party]] leader and [[Leader of the Opposition (Nova Scotia)|Leader of the Opposition]] from 1941 until the [[Nova Scotia general election, 1945|1945 provincial election]] wiped out the party.
Blois ran unsuccessfully for the [[House of Commons of Canada]] as the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] candidate in the riding of [[Colchester—Hants]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 1957|1957 federal election]]. He lost by 389 votes to the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] candidate. In 1960, he was summoned to the [[Senate of Canada]] representing the senatorial division of Colchester-Hants, Nova Scotia. He resigned in 1976.
