'''Khunying Kanitha Wichiencharoen''' (4 November 1920 – 13 May 2002) was a [[Thai people|Thai]] lawyer and women's rights advocate until late in life when she became a [[maechee]]. Most noted for her human rights work with women, she established the first emergency shelter for women in Thailand and wrote legislation to protect women's rights. She established the [[Mahapajapati Theri College]], the first college to train women as Buddhist nuns in southeast Asia.

==Early life==
Kanitha Samsen was born on 4 November 1920 in [[Bangkok]], in the [[History of Thailand|Kingdom of Siam]] to Thanom and Mangorn Samsen.{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}}{{sfn|Dharma Gateway|2007}} She was one of two daughters of the couple and her father was a well-known lawyer, who served as a senator during the transition to a [[constitutional monarchy]]. Her parents encouraged both Kanitha and her sister, Kanok, in their education.{{sfn|Dharma Gateway|2007}} Samsen began her studies at St. Francis Xavier Convent School and later attended St. Yoseph Convent School, before enrolling in law school at [[Thammasat University]]. After working for two years as a counselor with women who had suffered abuse and discrimination, Samsen moved to Washington, D. C.{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=207}} to study international law at [[American University]] and [[Columbia University]] in New York City.{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}} She then moved to Switzerland and studied international relations at the [[Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]] for the year in 1949.{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}}{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=207}}

==Career==
Returning to Bangkok, Samsen took a job at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, where she met Adul Wichiencharoen, whom she would marry in 1950 and with whom she would subsequently have three children: Aim, Anik, and Art.{{sfn|Library of Thammasat University|2016}}{{sfn||''The Thai Tribune''|2016}} In 1953, Wichiencharoen returned to the United States to study social welfare at [[Howard University]] in Washington, D. C.{{sfn|Falk|2007|pp=207–208}} Upon her graduation, in 1955, she returned to Thailand and worked as a supervisor at the [[Standard Vacuum Oil Company]].{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}} She also worked for USAID and then as the legal advisor to the Tourist Authority. In 1961, she began a three-year term as president of the Women Lawyer's Association of Thailand, traveling abroad as her duties required. As she visited other countries, she sought out women's shelters, intent on finding ways to improve services to women.{{sfn|Library of Thammasat University|2016}}{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}} She also instituted Saturday workshops where women lawyers gave ''[[pro bono]]'' legal advice to the public as a way of offering community assistance.{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}} Becoming the executive secretary of the Thai-American Technical Cooperation Association in 1963, she would serve in that capacity for the organization for the next twenty-one years.{{sfn|Dharma Gateway|2007}}{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}} In addition, she advised as a legal counselor to the United Nations, various developmental NGOs and the petroleum industry.{{sfn|Fouque|Veil|1992|p=16}}

In 1969, Wichiencharoen was selected as president of the International Women's Association of Thailand.{{sfn|Library of Thammasat University|2016}} Participating in the Thai women's rights movement actively throughout the 1970s, in 1974, Wichiencharoen became a founder of [http://www.apsw-thailand.org/indexEN.html The Association for the Promotion of the Status of Women] (APSW). The association, made up of both women and men began campaigning to revise and amend laws to provide better protections for women and children.{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}}{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}} She served as president of the organization and simultaneously became chair of the  National Council of Women's standing committee on Women and Labor.{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}} Because there were no facilities available in Thailand to assist abused, unemployed and elderly women, Wichiencharoen opened her home to serve as an emergency shelter. When the police did not know what to do with endangered women, they brought them to her.{{sfn|Tsomo|2013|pp=274–275}} She traveled extensively studying the situation of women around the world, participating in numerous conferences and academic experiences, such as a 1961 study of the family and youth courts of Japan; a 1977 assessment of the Australian family court and women’s shelters; a 1979 study tour which included observations at the Kansas City Women's Center, shelters in San Francisco and Washington, D.C., and a rape crisis center in New York; 1987 participation in the Federation of Soviet Women Congress in Prague; 1988 lecturer at the Nordic forum and Swedish Women’s Association, among many others.{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}}

In 1980, in response to needs identified by the Lawyer's Association, Wichiencharoen began a funding drive to establish a permanent [[women's shelter]]. Raising ฿50,000 ($2,000 US), APSW set up a shelter in the building of the Lawyer's association, offering housing, meals and medical referrals.{{sfn|Foster|1987}} The first [[women's shelter]] in Thailand, the Emergency Home and Relief Fund for Women and Children in Distress overflowed with clients.{{sfn|Library of Thammasat University|2016}} By 1986, they had outgrown their original space and opened a second and then a third home in the [[Don Mueang District|Donmuang District]] of Bangkok.{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}} Recognizing that their assistance was being provided after-the-fact, Wichiencharoen began raising funds to open an educational facility. The Women's Education and Training Center (WE-TRAIN), providing educational as well as vocational training, was established in 1988.{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}}{{sfn|Foster|1987}} Long wanting to develop a clinic to assist with pregnant women, in response to the growing needs of women after the [[HIV/AIDS in Thailand|HIV/AIDS epidemic]] was identified in the 1980s, a clinic was finally established.{{sfn|Dharma Gateway|2007}}{{sfn|Foster|1987}} 

In 1990, Wichiencharoen founded a policy research center to analyze and advise on socio-economic and political issues impacting women's lives. The Gender and Development Research Institute (GDRI), was established as an NGO, and works across the spectrum of social class to improve the welfare of women.{{sfn|Library of Thammasat University|2016}} Long aware of the discrepancies in the [[Buddhist faith]] regarding women in the ministry, and the subservience required of nuns to monks,{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=208}}{{sfn|Avila|2008|p=77}} Wichiencharoen became ordained as a ''[[maechee]]'' or "lay nun" in Sri Lanka in 1993.{{sfn|Falk|2007|pp=11–12}} Keeping her title, ''[[khunying]]'', the equivalent of the British ''[[dame]]'', she received criticism from the media, but because the king had bestowed the title and failure to use it would be a sign of disrespect, she took the name Maechee Khunying Kanitha. As she was still involved in the advocacy work of APSW, she also did not choose to live in the ''[[Convent|samnak chii]]'' with the other nuns, but established a separate cottage where she lived with a few other members of the community.{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=12}} In 1996, she drew up and lobbied for passage of the Nun's Bill of Rights advocating that women in religious orders should have political autonomy protected by law and have sole authority for allocating their funding ad determining ordination or censure of members. Though the bill failed,{{sfn|Avila|2008|p=82}} she continued to press for measures to improve the perceptions and opportunities of nuns. In 1999, Maechee Khunying Kanitha, working with the Thai Nun's Institute and APSW founded the first college, Mahapajapati Theri College, to offer women a bachelor of arts degree in Buddhism and philosophy.{{sfn|Library of Thammasat University|2016}}

==Death and legacy==
Wichiencharoen died on 13 May 2002{{sfn|Falk|2007|p=22}} from cancer.{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}} She is recognized as a pioneer of women's rights advocacy in Thailand {{sfn|Tsomo|2013|p=61}}{{sfn|Reynolds|1993|p=30}} In 1990, at the festivities held at the [[Sorbonne]] in honor of [[International Women's Day]], Wichiencharoen was honored as an outstanding advocate for women{{sfn|Fouque|Veil|1992|p=16}}{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}} and in 1995, she received an [[honorary doctorate]] in Philosophy, Sociology and Anthropology from [[Ramkhamhaeng University]].{{sfn|ทองหล่อ|2015}} 

