====Pitch and tone====
Pitch and tone are also important when speaking Sauk.{{how|date=March 2016}}
{{Clear}}

====Syllables====
Both the Sauk and Fox languages are known for [[apocope|"swallowing" syllables in word-final position]], which can make identification of individual sounds more difficult for the language learner.{{page needed|date=March 2016}}

===Morphology===
Sauk is a [[polysynthetic language]]. Because this can easily pose great difficulties to learners with little to no experience with highly synthetic languages<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/i-love-sauk-language|title=I love Sauk Language {{!}} Cultural Survival|website=www.culturalsurvival.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.native-languages.org/sf_guide.htm|title=Mesquakie-Sauk Pronunciation Guide, Alphabet and Phonology (Sac and Fox)|website=www.native-languages.org|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Müller|first=Reinschmidt, Kerstin|date=1995-01-01|title=Language Preservation With The Help Of Written Language: The Sauk Language Of The Sac And Fox Of Oklahoma|url=http://ehrafworldcultures.yale.edu/ehrafe/citation.do?method=citation&forward=browseAuthorsFullContext&id=np05-094|issn=0831-5671}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}, the Sauk orthography has words written by identifying each syllable.{{clarify|date=March 2016}}

